            <div class="content__page-desc">
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <b>Clean the Condenser Coils</b>
                  <p>
                    Condenser coils are responsible for releasing heat from the
                    refrigerator. Over time, they can become clogged with dust
                    and debris, causing the appliance to work harder and use
                    more energy. Clean the coils every six months using a vacuum
                    or a coil brush. This simple task can improve your
                    refrigerator’s efficiency and prevent potential breakdowns.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <b>Inspect and Clean the Door Seals</b>
                  <p>
                    The door seals (gaskets) are crucial for maintaining the
                    internal temperature of the refrigerator. Check the seals
                    for any cracks or wear and clean them regularly with a damp
                    cloth and mild detergent. A damaged or dirty seal can cause
                    cool air to escape, making the refrigerator work harder and
                    increasing your energy bills.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <b>Defrost the Freezer</b>
                  <p>
                    If your refrigerator doesn't have an automatic defrost
                    feature, you’ll need to manually defrost the freezer section
                    when ice buildup exceeds a quarter-inch. Ice buildup can
                    reduce the efficiency of your refrigerator and take up
                    valuable storage space. Turn off the refrigerator, remove
                    the contents, and let the ice melt naturally. Wipe down the
                    interior before turning the appliance back on.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <b>Check the Temperature Settings</b>
                  <p>
                    Ensure that your refrigerator and freezer are set to the
                    recommended temperatures. The ideal temperature for the
                    refrigerator compartment is between 37°F and 40°F (3°C and
                    4°C), while the freezer should be set at 0°F (-18°C). Proper
                    temperature settings help preserve food quality and reduce
                    energy consumption.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <b>Clean the Drain Hole and Drip Pan</b>
                  <p>
                    Refrigerators typically have a drain hole and drip pan to
                    collect and evaporate condensation. Over time, these can
                    become clogged with debris, leading to water leaks. Clean
                    the drain hole with a pipe cleaner or a similar tool and
                    wash the drip pan with mild soap and water. Regular cleaning
                    prevents mold growth and unpleasant odors.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <b>Organize and Rotate Food</b>
                  <p>
                    Keeping your refrigerator organized not only makes it easier
                    to find items but also allows for better air circulation.
                    Avoid overloading the shelves and rotate food items to
                    ensure they are used before their expiration date. Proper
                    organization can help maintain consistent temperatures and
                    reduce the workload on your refrigerator.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <b>Professional Maintenance Service</b>
                  <p>
                    Consider scheduling a professional maintenance service at
                    least once a year. Technicians can perform a thorough
                    cleaning of the drain line, filter, and moving components
                    such as the fan and motor. They can also assess the overall
                    condition of your refrigerator and address any potential
                    issues before they become major problems.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
