            </div>

            <div class="content__page-desc">
              <p>
                Deciding whether to repair or replace a refrigerator can be a
                challenging decision. Here are some factors to consider that can
                help you make an informed choice:
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="content__page-desc">
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <b>Age of the Refrigerator</b>
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      Lifespan: The average lifespan of a refrigerator is around
                      10-20 years. If your refrigerator is over 10 years old,
                      you might want to consider replacing it.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      Warranty: Check if your refrigerator is still under
                      warranty. If it is, repairs may be covered, making it a
                      more cost-effective option.
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <b>Cost of Repairs vs. Replacement</b>
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      Repair Costs: Get an estimate for the repair costs. If the
                      cost of repairs is more than 50% of the cost of a new
                      refrigerator, it may be more economical to replace it.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      Replacement Costs: Compare the cost of repairs with the
                      price of a new refrigerator. Don’t forget to factor in
                      delivery and installation fees.
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <b>Energy Efficiency</b>
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      Energy Consumption: Older models are usually less
                      energy-efficient compared to newer ones. A new
                      refrigerator could save you money on your electricity
                      bills
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      Energy Star Rating: Look for refrigerators with an Energy
                      Star rating, which are more efficient and environmentally
                      friendly.
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <b>Performance and Features</b>
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      Cooling Issues: If your refrigerator is consistently not
                      cooling properly, it might be a sign of a major issue.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      Features: Modern refrigerators come with advanced features
                      like smart technology, better storage options, and
                      improved temperature control. Assess if these features are
                      important to you.
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <b>Frequency of Repairs</b>
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      History of Repairs: If your refrigerator has needed
                      multiple repairs in the past few years, it may be reaching
                      the end of its useful life.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      Reliability: Continuous breakdowns can be inconvenient and
                      may indicate that it’s time for a replacement.
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <b>Environmental Impact</b>
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      Recycling: Consider the environmental impact of disposing
                      of your old refrigerator. Many manufacturers offer
                      recycling programs for old appliances.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      Eco-Friendly Options: Newer models are generally more
                      eco-friendly and have a lower carbon footprint.
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <b>Availability of Parts</b>
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      Parts Availability: For older models, it might be
                      difficult to find replacement parts, making repairs more
                      complicated and expensive.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      Technician Expertise: Ensure that local technicians are
                      familiar with your refrigerator model and can perform the
                      necessary repairs.
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <b>Personal Circumstances</b>
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      Budget: Assess your financial situation. If you're on a
                      tight budget, repairing might be the only viable option.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      Timing: Consider the timing. If you’re planning to move
                      soon, you might prefer a temporary repair over a full
                      replacement.
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </div>

            <div class="content__page-desc">
              <h3>Steps to Make a Decision</h3>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <b>Assess the Condition: </b>List the issues your refrigerator
