                      responsible for cooling the refrigerator. A clicking sound
                      may indicate that the compressor is trying to start but is
                      unable to do so. This could be due to a faulty start relay
                      or capacitor.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <b>Check the Start Relay: </b>The start relay helps the
                      compressor start up. If it's defective, it can cause a
                      clicking noise. You may need to replace the start relay to
                      resolve the issue.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <b>Look for Ice Build-Up: </b>Excessive ice build-up
                      around the evaporator coils can cause clicking sounds.
                      Defrost your refrigerator if you notice ice accumulation.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <b>Inspect the Defrost Timer: </b>The defrost timer
                      controls the defrost cycle of the refrigerator. If it's
                      faulty, it can produce clicking noises. Consider replacing
                      the defrost timer if necessary.
